<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-261-437  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 261 437.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Jan 1989 v12 n1 p64(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fashion CAD sets the pace. (computer-aided design at Nike Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hussey, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nike Inc uses Concept 2D, a turnkey CAD system from ComputerDesign Inc (CDI), to design athletic footwear and apparel.andP;  Thesystem's Fashion Design Module enables users to representcombinations of materials and textures that depict how shoes willlook before they are built.andP;  And there is a module called 3DDesign, which digitizes a shoe three-dimensionally, enables shoesto be constructed in a 3D environment, and creates sized shoepatterns.andP;  The system can also be used to output color separationsfor silkscreening applications, can create presentation slides formanagement and marketing, and can expedite the evaluation of coloralternatives.andP;  Nike employees have been slow to accept Concept 2Das a product development tool, however, and this is attributedboth to the learning curve and to computerphobia.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Nike Inc. (automation)Computer Design Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Concept 2D (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignSystemsApplicationsFunctional CapabilitiesFashion IndustryTurnkey SystemsDesign.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>